---
/**
 * storage-engines · storage-engines-fundamentals · Figure 6 — Level 6, each data
 * model (relational / document / graph) makes a different relationship cheap.
 *
 * Copied VERBATIM from the source page (figure + svg + figcaption). This figure
 * references no markers, so it needs no local <defs>.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 560 160"
        role="img"
        aria-label="Each model makes one relationship cheap and another expensive"
    >
        <g font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,sans-serif">
            <!-- relational -->
            <rect x="14" y="28" width="166" height="106" rx="9" fill="#fbfaf2" stroke="#1f3a5a"
            ></rect>
            <text x="97" y="46" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#1f3a5a"
                >RELATIONAL</text
            >
            <text x="97" y="66" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#2f5d3a"
                >+ ad-hoc joins, integrity</text
            >
            <text x="97" y="80" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#2f5d3a"
                >+ each fact stored once</text
            >
            <text x="97" y="100" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#9a2417"
                >− rich object = many joins</text
            >
            <text x="97" y="120" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f"
                >relate by value (FK)</text
            >
            <!-- document -->
            <rect x="196" y="28" width="166" height="106" rx="9" fill="#fbfaf2" stroke="#7a1f12"
            ></rect>
            <text
                x="279"
                y="46"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="11"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#7a1f12">DOCUMENT</text
            >
            <text x="279" y="66" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#2f5d3a"
                >+ load one aggregate, 1 read</text
            >
            <text x="279" y="80" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#2f5d3a"
                >+ maps to object tree</text
            >
            <text x="279" y="100" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#9a2417"
                >− cross-doc joins, shared data</text
            >
            <text x="279" y="120" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f"
                >embed contiguously</text
            >
            <!-- graph -->
            <rect x="378" y="28" width="166" height="106" rx="9" fill="#fbfaf2" stroke="#2f5d3a"
            ></rect>
            <text
                x="461"
                y="46"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="11"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#2f5d3a">GRAPH</text
            >
            <text x="461" y="66" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#2f5d3a"
                >+ many-hop traversal cheap</text
            >
            <text x="461" y="80" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#2f5d3a"
                >+ edge is first-class</text
            >
            <text x="461" y="100" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#9a2417"
                >− global aggregates awkward</text
            >
            <text x="461" y="120" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f"
                >follow stored pointers</text
            >
            <text x="280" y="152" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" fill="#6b675f"
                >choose by the dominant access pattern — not by fashion</text
            >
        </g>
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        "Friends-of-friends-of-friends" is a 3-table self-join (relational) but a 3-hop pointer walk
        (graph) — same data, opposite cost.
    </figcaption>
</figure>
